Protein Name: Amyloid protein A (AA); serum amyloid A protein
Reference: Zhang B, Une Y, Fu X, Yan J, Ge F, Yao J, Sawashita J, Mori M, Tomozawa H, Kametani F, Higuchi K. _Fecal transmission of AA amyloidosis in the cheetah contributes to high incidence of disease. _Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A. 2008 May 20;105(20):7263-8. Epub 2008 May 12. _18474855|Liu Y, Cui D, Hoshii Y, Kawano H, Une Y, Gondo T, Ishihara T. _Induction ofmurine AA amyloidosis by various homogeneous amyloid fibrils and amyloid-likesynthetic peptides. _Scand J Immunol. 2007 Nov;66(5):495-500. _17953525|Sponarova J, Nyström SN, Westermark GT. _AA-amyloidosis can be transferred byperipheral blood monocytes. _PLoS One. 2008 Oct 2;3(10):e3308. _18830411
Comment: In reference [1], transmission of AA amyloidosis to mice from cheetah feces containing AA amyloid was demonstrated. Amyloid preparations from feces had greater transmissibility than fromother sources. However, the mice in these experiments were primed for amyloidogenesis, by injection with silver nitrate for several days.| Transmissibility was also demonstrated in reference [2], with demonstration ofa species barrier analogous to that observed for PrP. Laboratory mice were primed for amyloidosis through injection of casein for several days| Evidence of cell-to-cell transmission mechanismshas been observed [3]|

Reference: Kane MD, Lipinski WJ, Callahan MJ, Bian F, Durham RA, Schwarz RD, Roher AE, Walker LC. _Evidence for seeding of beta -amyloid by intracerebral infusion of Alzheimer brain extracts in beta -amyloid precursor protein-transgenic mice._ J Neurosci. 2000 May 15;20(10):3606-11._10804202 |Meyer-Luehmann M, Coomaraswamy J, Bolmont T, Kaeser S, Schaefer C, Kilger E, Neuenschwander A, Abramowski D, Frey P, Jaton AL, Vigouret JM, Paganetti P, Walsh DM, Mathews PM, Ghiso J, Staufenbiel M, Walker LC, Jucker M._Exogenous induction of cerebral beta-amyloidogenesis is governed by agent and host._Science. 2006 Sep 22;313(5794):1781-4. _16990547 |Nussbaum JM, Schilling S, Cynis H, Silva A, Swanson E, Wangsanut T, Tayler K, Wiltgen B, Hatami A, Ronicke R, Reymann K, Hutter-Paier B, Alexandru A, Jagla W, Graubner S, Glabe CG, Demuth HU, Bloom GS._Prion-like behaviour and tau-dependent cytotoxicity of pyroglutamylated amyloid-beta._Nature. 2012 May 2;485(7400):651-5._22660329|Stohr J, Watts JC, Mensinger ZL, Oehler A, Grillo SK, DeArmond SJ, Prusiner SB, Giles K._Purified and synthetic Alzheimer's amyloid beta (Abeta) prions._Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A. 2012 Jul 3;109(27):11025-30._22711819|Rosen RF, Fritz JJ, Dooyema J, Cintron AF, Hamaguchi T, Lah JJ, LeVine H 3rd, Jucker M, Walker LC._Exogenous seeding of cerebral β-amyloid deposition in βAPP-transgenic rats. _ J Neurochem. 2012 Mar;120(5):660-6. doi: 10.1111/j.1471-4159.2011.07551.x. Comment: Intracerebral injection of A-beta-containing brain extracts caused cerebral beta-amyloidosis (refs. 1 and 2), with a dependence on host and source proteins that suggested the existence of A-beta prion strains| Low-n oligomers isolated from human Alzheimer's disease brains contained pyroglutamated A-beta that triggered neuronal damage and loss in lab mice at 3 months,in a tau-dependent manner (ref. 3) | Intracerebral inoculation of preparations of purely synthetic A-beta amyloid and of A-beta amyloid purified from human Alzheimer's brains caused A-beta amyloidosis in mice [ref. 4]. However, these mice can spontaneously acquire amyloidosis without such inoculations |Intracerebral injection of A-beta brain extracts into a transgenic rat model that does not otherwise develop A-beta deposition, causes A-beta amyloidosis [ref. 5]. These results indicate that A-beta might be a prion protein; however, the amyloid inoculations are derived from brain extracts, and not generated in vitro, so it is unclear whether additional co-factors in the brain extracts are necessary|Interacts with PD0015 , determined by: surface plasmon resonance|

Comment: TDP-43 cytoplasmic aggregates are implicated in ALS. TDP-43 contains a domain with yeast prion-like composition, whose aggregation has been re-capitulated in a budding yeast model     proteinopathy, and which profoundly affects yeast colony growth [1,2]. These aggregates are not amyloid-like. The TDP-43 C-terminus physically interacts with itself or with the Sup35 prion domain to form aggregates. This quasi-prion behaviour modulates known cellular functions of TDP-43 [3]

Comment: The functional form of MAVS is an amyloid-like aggregate that can co-opt other copies of the protein into the aggregated form. The aggregates are made from residues 1-218 of MAVS, which includes a CARD domain. This form plays a role in the assembly of anti-viral signaling complexes on the mitochondrial membrane [1,2].This mode of formation is similar to the functional intra-cellular assembly of CPEB (PD2090). MAVS aggregates that are formed in vitro can be introduced into cells to propagate the aggregated form to other copies of the MAVS protein, in the absence of viral infection. However, since these cells are cell lines derived from a metazoan organism, we do not classify MAVS as a prion (if it was it would be an Am* prion).  |

Comment: [MOD+] is heritable through cytoduction and through injection of in-vitro-made recombinant prions|[MOD+] prion aggregates sequester soluble MOD5, resulting in decreased levels of (i6A)-modified tRNAs and higher ergosterol levels, due to less competition for ERG20 (P08524), which uses the same substrate DMAPP as MOD5. [MOD+] can be cured by GdnHCl and by deletion of the molecular chaperone Hsp104 (P31539), which is required for [MOD+] propagation. The [MOD+] state acquires resistance against antifungal agents that inhibit ergosterol biosynthesis.De novo appearance of [MOD+] is favored by the presence of antifungal agents, and the growth advantage of [MOD+] is lost when the cells are released from the selective pressure. Thus, the conformational switch of MOD5 from a soluble state to a prion state allows the cell to adapt to the harmful environment of anti-fungal drugs by up-regulating ergosterol biosynthesis at the expense of tRNA modification.|
